ance in a few Indian movies:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Film\n!Language\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|2005\n|''[[Kaydyacha Bola]]'' \n|Marathi\n|Thambi\n|Special appearance\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Mumbai Meri Jaan]]''\n|Hindi\n|\n|\n|-\n|2013\n|''[[Aajcha Divas Majha]]''\n|Marathi\n|Satam\n|\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Vakratunda Mahakaaya]]''\n|Marathi\n|Secretary\n|\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[A Paying Ghost]]''\n|Marathi\n|Ganpule\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|''Mumbai Time'' \n|Marathi\n|\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|[[Vikun Taak]]\n|Marathi\n|\n|\n|}\n\n==Theater work==\nSamir is an actor in Marathi Theater and below are a few plays where he has acted in:\n# ''Asa Mi Asa Mi'' \n# ''Varya Varchi varat'' \n# ''Vyakti Ani Valli'' \n# ''Yada kadachit''\n# ''Chalre Bhoplya Tunuk Tunuk'' \n# ''Balak Palak'' \n# ''Shri Bai Samartha''\n# ''Carry On Heavens'' (Hinglish drama by Bharat Dabholkar)\n# ''Best of Bottoms Up'' (English Drama)\n#Hyancha Kaay Karaaycha\n\n== TV appearances ==\nSamir has also acted in a few TV serials:\n# ''Tikal te Political''  (Political satire by Chandrakant Kulkarni) \n# ''Ambat God''<ref>{{cite web |title=Ambat Goad 4 Days Remaining |date=6 December 2012 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RC9OmokIuEE |website=Youtube.com |accessdate=28 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/samir-choughule/credits/900557/ |title=Samir Choughule |website=TVGuide.com |access-date=28 June 2016}}</ref> \n# ''Honar sun me tya gharchi''  (Special appearance as Pappu) \n# Comedy chi bullet train (Color Marathi)\n# ''Kunku'' \n# ''Aajke Shriman Shrimati''  (Hindi TV Serial)\n# ''Maharashtrachi Hasya Jatra'' (Sony Marathi)\n#Saare Tuzyachsathi (Sony Marathi)\n\n==Awards and recognition==\n# Sanskruti kaladarpan Natya vibhag \u2013 2016<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sanskrutikaladarpan.com/gaurav-rajni.html |title=Sanskruti Kaladarpan \u2013 Official website |website=Sanskrutikaladarpan.com |access-date=28 June 2016}}</ref>\n# Zee Natya Gourav Puraskar 2015 \u2013 Best Comedy Actor for drama \u2013 Balak Palak<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x2kvs8y |title=Zee Natya Gaurav 2015 Award Winners Reaction-TV9 \u2013 Video Dailymotion |website=Dailymotion |access-date=28 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web |url=http://f2fentertainment.com/zee-natyagaurav-nominations/ |title=Zee NatyaGaurav Nominations - Full2Fatak |website=F2fentertainment.com |date=20 June 2014 |accessdate=15 November 2016}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://maharashtratimes.indiatimes.com/business/property/propertytimes-sameer-chaughule-house/articleshow/50605577.cms |title=propertytimes sameer chaughule house - Maharashtra Times |website=Maharashtratimes.indiatimes.com |date= |accessdate=15 November 2016}}\n* {{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZCNWkOw-E6E |title=Samir Choughule Dream Home - Saam Tv |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=1 March 2013 |accessdate=15 November 2016}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Choughule, Samir}}\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Maharashtra]]\n", "name_user": "Chandra002", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samir_Choughule"}
{"title_page": "Victoria, Bra\u0219ov", "text_new": "{{no footnotes|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = town\n|county                 = Bra\u0219ov\n|population_total       = auto\n|coordinates            = {{coord|45|44|34|N|24|41|24|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|map_caption = Location in Bra\u0219ov County\n|image_skyline= Victoria (Romania), le 3 mai 2007.jpg\n|official_name=Victoria\n|image_map=Victoria jud Brasov.jpg\n|image_shield=\n|leader_name=Gheorghe Cristian<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.2016bec.ro/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/SIAL2016_P_Lista_Moc-2.xlsx |title=Results of the 2016 local elections |publisher=Central Electoral Bureau |accessdate=2020-04-03 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|leader_party=PNL\n|area_total_km2=6.47\n|website={{url|http://www.primariavictoria.ro/}}\n}}\n\n'''Victoria''' ({{IPA-ro|vik\u02c8tori.a}}; {{lang-de|Viktoriastadt}}; {{lang-hu|Vikt\u00f3riav\u00e1ros}}) is a town in the western part of [[Bra\u0219ov County]], [[Romania]], near the [[F\u0103g\u0103ra\u0219 Mountains]]. It had a population of 7,067 at the 2011 census.\n\nIn 1939, the Romanian state signed a contract with the German company Ferrostaal of [[Essen]] to build a factory (called \"Ucea\") on the site of what is now Victoria. The contract was canceled after Romania declared war on Germany in 1944, during [[World War II]].\n\nThe building of the town began in 1949 and it had the provisional names of \"Colonia Ucea\" and \"Ucea Ro\u0219ie\" (Red Ucea), only to be changed in November 1954 to Victoria.\n{{Historical populations\n|source = Census data\n|1956 |2762\n|1966 |6717\n|1977 |8209\n|1992 |10247\n|2002 |9059\n|2011 |7067\n}}\n\n==Twin towns ==\n* {{flagicon|France}} [[Chevilly-Larue]], [[France]] (1994)\n* {{flagicon|Netherlands}} [[Utrechtse Heuvelrug]], [[Netherlands]] (2005)\n* {{flagicon|Italy}} [[Lariano]], [[Italy]] (2007)\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Victoria, Romania}}\n* [http://www.orasulvictoria.ro www.orasulvictoria.ro]\n\n{{Bra\u015fov-geo-stub}}\n{{Bra\u015fov County}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Victoria, Brasov}}\n[[Category:Monotowns in Romania]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1949]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Bra\u0219ov County]]\n[[Category:Planned cities in Romania]]\n[[Category:Socialist planned cities]]\n[[Category:Towns in Romania]]\n", "text_old": "{{no footnotes|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = town\n|county                 = Bra\u0219ov\n|population_total       = auto\n|coordinates            = {{coord|45|44|34|N|24|41|24|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|map_caption = Location in Bra\u0219ov County\n|image_skyline= Victoria (Romania), le 3 mai 2007.jpg\n|official_name=Victoria\n|image_map=Victoria jud Brasov.jpg\n|image_shield=\n|leader_name=Gheorghe Cristian\n|leader_party=PDL\n|area_total_km2=6.47\n|website={{url|http://www.primariavictoria.ro/}}\n}}\n\n'''Victoria''' ({{IPA-ro|vik\u02c8tori.a}}; {{lang-de|Viktoriastadt}}; {{lang-hu|Vikt\u00f3riav\u00e1ros}}) is a town in the western part of [[Bra\u0219ov County]], [[Romania]], near the [[F\u0103g\u0103ra\u0219 Mountains]]. It had a population of 7,067 at the 2011 census.\n\nIn 1939, the Romanian state signed a contract with the German company Ferrostaal of [[Essen]] to build a factory (called \"Ucea\") on the site of what is now Victoria. The contract was canceled after Romania declared war on Germany in 1944, during [[World War II]].\n\nThe building of the town began in 1949 and it had the provisional names of \"Colonia Ucea\" and \"Ucea Ro\u0219ie\" (Red Ucea), only to be changed in November 1954 to Victoria.\n{{Historical populations\n|source = Census data\n|1956 |2762\n|1966 |6717\n|1977 |8209\n|1992 |10247\n|2002 |9059\n|2011 |7067\n}}\n\n==Twin towns ==\n* {{flagicon|France}} [[Chevilly-Larue]], [[France]] (1994)\n* {{flagicon|Netherlands}} [[Utrechtse Heuvelrug]], [[Netherlands]] (2005)\n* {{flagicon|Italy}} [[Lariano]], [[Italy]] (2007)\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Victoria, Romania}}\n* [http://www.orasulvictoria.ro www.orasulvictoria.ro]\n\n{{Bra\u015fov-geo-stub}}\n{{Bra\u015fov County}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Victoria, Brasov}}\n[[Category:Monotowns in Romania]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1949]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Bra\u0219ov County]]\n[[Category:Planned cities in Romania]]\n[[Category:Socialist planned cities]]\n[[Category:Towns in Romania]]\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Victoria,_Bra%C8%99ov"}
{"title_page": "Jonas \u00c5kerlund", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{about|the director|the politician|Jonas \u00c5kerlund (politician)}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                      = Jonas \u00c5kerlund\n| image                     = Jonas Akerlund.jpg\n| image_size                = \n| caption                   = \u00c5kerlund in 2012\n| birth_name                = Hans Uno Jonas \u00c5kerlund\n| birth_date                = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1965|11|10}}\n| birth_place               = [[Bromma]], [[Stockholm]], [[Sweden]]\n| occupation                = {{flatlist|\n* Film director\n* screenwriter\n* music video director\n* drummer\n}}\n| years_active              = 1983\u2013present\n| death_date      =\n| spouse                    = Bea \u00c5kerlund\n| website                   =\n}}\n\n'''Hans Uno Jonas \u00c5kerlund''' ({{IPA-sv|h\u0251\u02d0ns \u02c8\u0289\u030c\u02d0n\u028a \u02c8j\u00fb\u02d0nas \u02c8\u00f4\u02d0k\u025b\u02cc\u026d\u0275nd|lang}}; born 10 November 1965) is a Swedish film director, screenwriter, music video director, and drummer. His video for [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]'s song \"[[Ray of Light (song)|Ray of Light]]\" won a [[Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Short Form Music Video|Best Music Video, Short Form]], and a record seven awards at [[1998 MTV Video Music Awards]], including the [[MTV Video Music Award for Video of the Year|Video of the Year]].\n\nIn 2008 he won another Grammy Award, this time around for \"Best Long Form Music Video\" for another work with Madonna \u2013 directing \"The Confessions Tour\" DVD. In 2014 he won this Grammy Award again (that meanwhile changed the name to \"Best Music Film\"), this time for \"Live Kisses\" [[Paul McCartney]] concert film. Jonas \u00c5kerlund, [[David Mallet (director)|David Mallet]] and Bob Smeaton are the only directors to have won this award twice sharing the record for most wins in this category (check here all winners and nominees of [[Grammy Award for Best Music Film]]).\n\n==Career==\n\u00c5kerlund was a member of the Swedish [[black metal]] band [[Bathory (band)|Bathory]] from 1983 to 1984. He also directed Candlemass' first video \"Bewitched\". He first found fame as the main video director for [[Roxette]]. In 1997, he directed the acclaimed video for [[The Prodigy]]'s \"[[Smack My Bitch Up]]\", which sparked controversy due to its depiction of drug use, violence, and nudity. In 1998, he worked with [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] for the song \"[[Ray of Light (song)|Ray of Light]]\", and has since worked with acts such as [[Metallica]], [[Christina Aguilera]], [[U2]], [[Blink-182]], [[P!nk]], [[Rammstein]], [[Britney Spears]], and [[Lady Gaga]]. He directed the music video for the [[Smashing Pumpkins]]' \"Try, Try, Try\", from which a short film entitled ''Try'' was spawned. He was also the designer and photographer for the [[Roxette]] album ''[[Room Service (Roxette album)|Room Service]]'' in 2001. In 2002, his first full-length film, ''[[Spun]]'', debuted.\n\n\u00c5kerlund directed commercials for Swedish clothing retailer MQ and the re-imagining of the Devo song \"Watch Us Work It\" used in [[Dell Computers]] commercials. He is a long-time collaborator of Madonna, having worked on such music videos as \"Music\", \"American Life\" (which was pulled due to its graphic content and the [[Iraq War]]), and \"Jump\". He also directed her documentary film ''[[I'm Going to Tell You a Secret]]'' and her concert special ''[[The Confessions Tour (album)|The Confessions Tour: Live from London]]''. Among his more recent works were the controversial pornographic music video for [[Rammstein]]'s \"[[Pussy (Rammstein song)|Pussy]]\", the video for the song \"[[Telephone (song)|Telephone]]\" by [[Lady Gaga]] and [[Beyonc\u00e9]], \"[[Moves like Jagger]]\" by [[Maroon 5]] and [[Christina Aguilera]], and [[Duran Duran]]'s single \"Girl Panic!\".<ref name=\"MTV gaga\">{{cite web|last=Wigler|first=Josh|title=The Man Behind Lady Gaga's 'Telephone' Video: Jonas Akerlund|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1633818/man-behind-lady-gagas-telephone-video-jonas-akerlund.jhtml|publisher=MTV|accessdate=24 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n\u00c5kerlund's second movie, ''[[Small Apartments]]'', went direct to DVD.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Citation|last=\u00c5kerlund|first=Jonas|title=Small Apartments|date=1 March 2013|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1272886/|accessdate=27 July 2016}}</ref> [[Per Gessle]], of Roxette, was credited for the music and soundtrack.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Videography==\n<!--[[Music video director]] links directly here.-->\n{{col-begin}}{{col-break|width=36%}}\n\n'''1988'''\n:\"Bewitched\" for [[Candlemass (band)|Candlemass]] \n'''1989'''\n:\"What's the Noise?\" for [[Walk on Water (band)|Walk on Water]]\n'''1992'''\n:\"[[Shame, Shame, Shame (Shirley & Company song)|Shame, Shame, Shame]]\" for [[Izabella Scorupco]]\n:\"S\u00e5 l\u00e4nge det lyser mittemot\" for [[Marie Fredriksson]] <small>(Female half of Roxette)</small>\n:\"Mellan sommar och h\u00f6st\" for Marie Fredriksson\n'''1993'''\n:\"[[Fingertips '93]]\" for [[Roxette]]\n'''1994'''\n:\"[[Run to You (Roxette song)|Run to You]]\" for Roxette\n'''1995'''\n:\"A la ronde\" for [[Sinclair (singer)|Sinclair]]\n:\"[[Vulnerable (song)|Vulnerable]]\" for Roxette\n:\"Pay for Me\" for [[Whale (band)|Whale]]\n'''1996'''\n:\"[[June Afternoon]]\" for Roxette\n:\"[[She Doesn't Live Here Anymore]]\" for Roxette\n:\"Un Dia Sin Ti\" for Roxette <small>(Spanish version of \"[[Spending My Time]]\")</small>\n'''1997''' \n:\"[[Do You Wanna Be My Baby?]]\" for [[Per Gessle]] <small>(Male half of Roxette)</small>\n:\"[[James Bond Theme#Moby Re-version|James Bond Theme]]\" for [[Moby]]\n:\"[[Kix (song)|Kix]]\" for Per Gessle\n:\"[[I Want You to Know (Per Gessle song)|I Want You To Know]]\" for Per Gessle\n:\"[[Smack My Bitch Up]]\" for [[The Prodigy]]\n'''1998'''\n:\"[[Ray of Light (song)|Ray of Light]]\" for [[Madonna (entertainer)|Mado